# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bazel-build
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Similar to build tools like Make, Apache Ant, and Apache Maven, Bazel builds software applications from source code using rules.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Rules and macros are created in the Starlark language, a dialect of Python.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] There are built-in rules for building software written in Java, Kotlin, Scala, C, C++, Go, Python, Rust, JavaScript, Objective-C, and bash scripts.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel can produce software application packages suitable for deployment for the Android and iOS operating systems.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] In 2006, Google started the development of a build tool called *Blaze*.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] The motivation was to have a build system that provides both speed and correctness in a large monorepo.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel was created as an open-source port of Blaze, using its anagram as a name.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel was first released in March 2015 and entered beta by September 2015.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Version 1.0 was released in October 2019.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel has been described as "one of the first openly available cloud build systems".
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] It is able to save the history of previously run commands and share the results across multiple users.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] To do so, Bazel requires that the inputs and outputs of build targets are fully specified.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel is extensible with the Starlark programming language.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Starlark is an embedded language whose syntax is a subset of the Python syntax.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] However, it doesn't implement many of Python's language features, such as the ability to access the file I/O, in order to avoid extensions that could create side-effects or create build outputs not known to the build system itself.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Such side-effects could potentially lead to incorrect analysis of the build dependency graph.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel was designed as a multilanguage build system.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] It is able to build software combining multiple programming languages within the same repository.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Many commonly used build systems are designed with a preference for a specific programming language.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Examples of such systems include Ant and Maven for Java, Leiningen for Clojure, sbt for Scala, etc.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] In a repository with multiple languages, combining separate build systems and achieving the build speed and correctness benefits described above can be difficult and problematic.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Build systems most similar to Bazel are Pants, Buck, Please, and the Brazil build system used internally at Amazon.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Pants and Buck both aim for similar technical design objectives as Bazel, with Pants being inspired by the Blaze build system used internally at Google.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel, Pants, Buck, and Please adopted Starlark as a BUILD file parser, respective to its BUILD file syntax.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Independently developed build systems with similar uses in efficient dependency graph analysis and automated build artifact tracking have been implemented in build systems such as tup.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Bazel uses a sandbox for compilation steps.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] When Bazel performs a separate compilation, it creates a new directory and fills it with symlinks to the explicit input dependencies for the rule.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] For languages like C or C++, this requires the user to be explicit about the dependencies and it prevents the unexpected inclusion of a similarly named header file from another including directory.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] This sandbox approach leads to issues with common build tools, resulting in a number of workarounds required to correctly compile code under different architectures.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] For example, when performing separate compilation for Mac/Darwin architectures, the compiler writes the input paths into SO and OSO symbols in the Mach-O binary, which can be seen with a command like `nm -a mybinary | grep SO`.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] These paths are needed for finding symbols during debugging.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] As a result, builds in Bazel must correct the compiled objects after the fact, trying to correct path-related issues that arose from the sandbox construction using flags like `-fdebug-prefix-map` and `-oso_prefix`, the latter having become available in Xcode 11.0.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Similar handling needs to take place in linking phases, rewriting the rpath values in shared object libraries with a command like `install_name_tool`.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] Since Bazel's initial release the logo was a green letter "b" stylized into a stem of a basil plant with two leaves.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] On July 5, 2017, the Bazel Blog announced a new logo, consisting of three green building blocks arranged to shape a heart.
[src:bazel-build/bazel-software] A few notable users include BMW, Google, SpaceX, Stripe, Tinder, and Uber.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:bazel-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Bazel builds software from source code organized in directory trees called repositories.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A defined set of repositories comprises the workspace.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Source files in repositories are organized in a nested hierarchy of packages, where each package is a directory that contains a set of related source files and one `BUILD` file.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The `BUILD` file specifies what software outputs can be built from the source.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Source files used in a Bazel build are organized in *repositories* (often shortened to *repos*).
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A repo is a directory tree with a boundary marker file at its root; such a boundary marker file could be `MODULE.bazel`, `REPO.bazel`, or in legacy contexts, `WORKSPACE` or `WORKSPACE.bazel`.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The repo in which the current Bazel command is being run is called the *main repo*.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Other, (external) repos are defined by *repo rules*; see external dependencies overview for more information.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A *workspace* is the environment shared by all Bazel commands run from the same main repo.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] It encompasses the main repo and the set of all defined external repos.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Note that historically the concepts of "repository" and "workspace" have been conflated; the term "workspace" has often been used to refer to the main repository, and sometimes even used as a synonym of "repository".
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The primary unit of code organization in a repository is the *package*.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A package is a collection of related files and a specification of how they can be used to produce output artifacts.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A package is defined as a directory containing a `BUILD` file named either `BUILD` or `BUILD.bazel`.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A package includes all files in its directory, plus all subdirectories beneath it, except those which themselves contain a `BUILD` file.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] From this definition, no file or directory may be a part of two different packages.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] For example, in the following directory tree there are two packages, `my/app`, and the subpackage `my/app/tests`.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Note that `my/app/data` is not a package, but a directory belonging to package `my/app`.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] A package is a container of *targets*, which are defined in the package's `BUILD` file.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Most targets are one of two principal kinds, *files* and *rules*.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Files are further divided into two kinds.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] *Source files* are usually written by the efforts of people, and checked in to the repository.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] *Generated files*, sometimes called derived files or output files, are not checked in, but are generated from source files.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The second kind of target is declared with a *rule*.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Each rule instance specifies the relationship between a set of input and a set of output files.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The inputs to a rule may be source files, but they also may be the outputs of other rules.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Whether the input to a rule is a source file or a generated file is in most cases immaterial; what matters is only the contents of that file.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] This fact makes it easy to replace a complex source file with a generated file produced by a rule, such as happens when the burden of manually maintaining a highly structured file becomes too tiresome, and someone writes a program to derive it.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] No change is required to the consumers of that file.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Conversely, a generated file may easily be replaced by a source file with only local changes.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The inputs to a rule may also include *other rules*.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The precise meaning of such relationships is often quite complex and language- or rule-dependent, but intuitively it is simple: a C++ library rule A might have another C++ library rule B for an input.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The effect of this dependency is that B's header files are available to A during compilation, B's symbols are available to A during linking, and B's runtime data is available to A during execution.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] An invariant of all rules is that the files generated by a rule always belong to the same package as the rule itself; it is not possible to generate files into another package.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] It is not uncommon for a rule's inputs to come from another package, though.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Package groups are sets of packages whose purpose is to limit accessibility of certain rules.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Package groups are defined by the `package_group` function.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] They have three properties: the list of packages they contain, their name, and other package groups they include.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] The only allowed ways to refer to them are from the `visibility` attribute of rules or from the `default_visibility` attribute of the `package` function; they do not generate or consume files.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] For more information, refer to the `package_group` documentation.
