[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] For details, see the Google Developers Site Policies.
[src:bazel-build/concepts-build-ref] Java is a registered trademark of Oracle and/or its affiliates.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The **incremental build model** is a method of software development where the product is designed, implemented, and tested incrementally (a little more is added each time) until the product is finished.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] It involves both development and maintenance.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The product is defined as finished when it satisfies all of its requirements.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] This model combines the elements of the waterfall model with the iterative philosophy of prototyping.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The product is decomposed into several components, each of which is designed and built separately (termed as builds).
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Each component is delivered to the client when it is complete.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] This allows partial use of the product and avoids a long development time.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] It also avoids a large initial capital outlay and subsequent long waiting periods.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] This model of development also helps ease the traumatic effect of introducing an all-new system all at once.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The incremental model applies the waterfall model incrementally.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The series of releases is referred to as “increments," with each increment providing more functionality to the customers.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] After the first increment, a core product is delivered, which can already be used by the customer.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Based on customer feedback, a plan is developed for the next increments, and modifications are made accordingly.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] This process continues, with increments being delivered until the complete product is delivered.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The incremental philosophy is also used in the agile process model (see agile modeling).
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The Incremental model can be applied to DevOps.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] DevOps centers around the idea of minimizing the risk and cost of a DevOps adoption whilst building the necessary in-house skillset and momentum.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Partial systems are built to produce the final system.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] First tackled the highest priority requirements.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] The requirement of a portion is frozen once the incremented portion is developed.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] It is generally easier to test and debug than other methods of software development because relatively smaller changes are made during each iteration.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] This allows for more targeted and rigorous testing of each element within the overall product.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Customers can respond to features and review the product for any needed or useful changes.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Initial product delivery is faster and costs less.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Planning: required as many people (software teams) to work on the same project but with different functions at the same time.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Modeling: involves business modeling, data modeling, and process modeling.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Construction: this involves the reuse of software components and automatic code.
[src:bazel-build/incremental-build-model] Deployment: integration of all the increments.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In software development, **Make** is a command-line interface software tool that performs actions ordered by configured dependencies as defined in a configuration file called a *makefile*.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] It is commonly used for build automation to build executable code (such as a program or library) from source code.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make is also not limited to building and can perform any operation available via the operating system shell.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make is widely used, especially in Unix and Unix-like operating systems, even though many competing technologies and tools are available, including similar tools that perform actions based on dependencies, some compilers and interactively via an integrated development environment.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In addition to referring to the original Unix tool, Make is also a technology since multiple tools have been implemented with roughly the same functionality – including similar makefile syntax and semantics.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Stuart Feldman created Make while at Bell Labs.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] An early version was completed in April 1976.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Feldman received the 2003 ACM Software System Award for authoring Make.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] — Stuart Feldman, *The Art of Unix Programming*, Eric S.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Before Make, building on Unix mostly consisted of shell scripts written for each program's codebase.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make's dependency ordering and out-of-date checking makes the build process more robust and more efficient.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The makefile allowed for better organization of build logic and often fewer build files.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make is widely used in part due to its early inclusion in Unix, starting with PWB/UNIX 1.0, which featured a variety of software development tools.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make has been implemented numerous times, generally using the same makefile format and providing the same features, but some providing enhancements from the original.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] POSIX includes standardization of the basic features and operation of the Make utility, and is implemented with varying degrees of compatibility with Unix-based versions of Make.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In general, simple makefiles may be used between various versions of Make with reasonable success.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] GNU Make, Makepp and some versions of BSD Make default to looking first for files named "GNUmakefile", "Makeppfile" and "BSDmakefile" respectively, which allows one to put makefiles which use implementation-defined behavior in separate locations.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In general, based on a makefile, Make updates target files from source files if any source file has a newer timestamp than the target file or the target file does not exist.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] For example, this could include compiling C files (`*.c`) into object files, then linking the object files into an executable program.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Or this could include compiling TypeScript files (`*.ts`) to JavaScript for use in a browser.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Other examples include: convert a source image file to another format, copy a file to a content management system, and send e-mail about build status.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A makefile defines targets where each is either a file to generate or is a user-defined concept, called a *phony* target.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] If no target is specified, Make updates the first target in the makefile which is often a phony target to perform the most commonly used action.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make skips build actions if the target file timestamp is after that of the source files.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Also, if a source file's timestamp is in the future, make repeatedly triggers unnecessary actions, causing longer build time.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] When Make starts, it uses the makefile specified on the command-line or if not specified, then uses the one found by via specific search rules.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Generally, Make defaults to using the file in the working directory named Makefile.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] GNU Make searches for the first file matching: GNUmakefile, makefile, or Makefile.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make processes the options of the command-line based on the loaded makefile.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The **makefile** language is partially declarative programming where end conditions are described but the order in which actions are to be taken is not.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Each rule begins with a *dependency line* which consists of the rule's target name followed by a colon (:), and optionally a list of targets (also known as prerequisites) on which the rule's target depends.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Usually a rule has a single target, rather than multiple.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A dependency line may be followed by a recipe: a series of TAB indented command lines that define how to generate the target from the components (i.e. source files).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] If any prerequisite has a more recent timestamp than the target file or the target does not exist as a file, the recipe is performed.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Each command line must begin with a tab character.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Even though a space is also whitespace, Make requires tab.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Since this often leads to confusion and mistakes, this aspect of makefile syntax is subject to criticism.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Raymond describes it as "one of the worst design botches in the history of Unix" and *The Unix-Haters Handbook* said "using tabs as part of the syntax is like one of those pungee [sic] stick traps in *The Green Berets*".
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Each command is executed in a separate shell.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Since operating systems use different shells, this can lead to unportable makefiles.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] For example, GNU Make (all POSIX Makes) executes commands with /bin/sh by default, where Unix commands like cp are normally used.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In contrast, Microsoft's *nmake* executes commands with cmd.exe where batch commands like copy are available but not necessarily cp.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The following example rule is evaluated when Make updates target file.txt via `make file.txt`.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] If file.html is newer than file.txt or file.txt does not exist, then the command is run to generate file.txt from file.html.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Ignoring errors and silencing echo can alternatively be obtained via the special targets `.IGNORE` and `.SILENT`.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Microsoft's NMAKE has predefined rules that can be omitted from these makefiles, e.g.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Macros are usually referred to as *variables* when they hold simple string definitions, like `CC=clang`.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Macros in makefiles may be overridden in the command-line arguments passed to the Make utility.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Environment variables are also available as macros.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] For example, the macro `CC` is frequently used in makefiles to refer to the location of a C compiler.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] If used consistently throughout the makefile, then the compiler used can be changed by changing the value of the macro rather than changing each rule command that invokes the compiler.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A macro value can consist of other macro values.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The value of macro is expanded on each use lazily.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A macro is used by expanding either via $*NAME* or $(*NAME*).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The latter is safer since omitting the parentheses leads to Make interpreting the next letter after the `$` as the entire variable name.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] An equivalent form uses curly braces rather than parentheses, i.e.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Macros can be composed of shell commands by using the command substitution operator `!=`.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Makefiles can access predefined *internal macros*, with `?` and `@` being common.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A common syntax when defining macros, which works on BSD and GNU Make, is to use +=, ?=, and != instead of the equal sign (=).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Suffix rules have "targets" with names in the form `.FROM.TO` and are used to launch actions based on file extension.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In the command lines of suffix rules, POSIX specifies that the internal macro `$<` refers to the first prerequisite and `$@` refers to the target.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Suffix rules cannot have any prerequisites of their own.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] If they have any, they are treated as normal files with unusual names, not as suffix rules.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] GNU Make supports suffix rules for compatibility with old makefiles but otherwise encourages usage of *pattern rules*.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A pattern rule looks like an ordinary rule, except that its target contains exactly one `%` character within the string.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The target is considered a pattern for matching file names: the `%` can match any substring of zero or more characters, while other characters match only themselves.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The prerequisites likewise use `%` to show how their names relate to the target name.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Single-line comments are started with the hash symbol (#).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] A directive specifies special behavior such as including another makefile.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Line continuation is indicated with a backslash `\` character at the end of a line.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The following commands are in the context of the makefile that follows.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Below is a simple makefile that by default (the "all" rule is listed first) compiles a source file called "helloworld.c" using the system's C compiler and also provides a "clean" target to remove the generated files if the user desires to start over.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The `$@` and `$<` are two of the so-called internal macros (also known as automatic variables) and stand for the target name and "implicit" source, respectively.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In the example below, `$^` expands to a space delimited list of the prerequisites.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] There are a number of other internal macros.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Many systems come with predefined Make rules and macros to specify common tasks such as compilation based on file suffix.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] This lets users omit the actual (often unportable) instructions of how to generate the target from the source(s).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] That "helloworld.o" depends on "helloworld.c" is now automatically handled by Make.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] In such a simple example as the one illustrated here this hardly matters, but the real power of suffix rules becomes evident when the number of source files in a software project starts to grow.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] One only has to write a rule for the linking step and declare the object files as prerequisites.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Make will then implicitly determine how to make all the object files and look for changes in all the source files.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Simple suffix rules work well as long as the source files do not depend on each other and on other files such as header files.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Another route to simplify the build process is to use so-called pattern matching rules that can be combined with compiler-assisted dependency generation.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] As a final example requiring the gcc compiler and GNU Make, here is a generic makefile that compiles all C files in a folder to the corresponding object files and then links them to the final executable.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Before compilation takes place, dependencies are gathered in makefile-friendly format into a hidden file ".depend" that is then included to the makefile.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Portable programs ought to avoid constructs used below.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Makefile consist of dependencies and a forgotten or an extra one may not be immediately obvious to the user and may result in subtle bugs in the generated software that are hard to catch.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Various approaches may be used to avoid this problem and keep dependencies in source and makefiles in sync.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] One approach is using the compiler to keep track of dependencies changes.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] GCC can statically analyze the source code and produce rules for the given file automatically by using the `-MM` switch.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] The other approach would be makefiles or third-party tools that would generate makefiles with dependencies (e.g.
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Automake toolchain by the GNU Project, can do so automatically).
[src:bazel-build/make-software] Another approach is to use meta-build tools like CMake, Meson etc.
